<h2 id="a-note-about-tuning-capo-and-how-dylan-plays-this-song">A note about tuning, capo, and how Dylan plays this song</h2>

<p>My video lesson &amp; this PDF teaches this song in standard tuning, using no capo ‚Äì as the goal of this arrangement is to keep things accessible &amp; approachable. But I should note, Dylan doesn‚Äôt play the song the way I am showing! He‚Äôs using capo 2nd fret, in open D tuning (D-A-D-F#-A-D). Maybe I‚Äôll make a lesson for playing this song that way someday, but note ‚Äì that‚Äôs not what I‚Äôm doing in this lesson.</p>

<h2 id="chord-shapes">Chord shapes</h2>

<p>At a glance, the chords I use are as follows (shown in tab form). For the E-Emaj7-E7 sequence, I prefer using the four-string voicing shown here as my foundation. This allows you to capture the sound of the descending bass note within those three chords, which is vital to capturing Dylan‚Äôs sound.</p>

<p>For the B chord, I‚Äôll use this Bsus4 voicing I show below ‚Äî which is far easier to play than a typical B-major chord (since you don‚Äôt have to barre anything). This version of the B also captures the vibe of Dylan‚Äôs version (via the thinnest two strings being open), which gives off an open-tuning sound.</p>

<p>For the A-major chord, I often will freely switch to an Asus2 to mix up the sound, which again captures the open-tuning vibe of Dylan‚Äôs version.</p>

